          "misconceptionId": "misc-03-pitch-equals-teach",
          "misconception": "The game pitch should explain how to play so the friend knows what they're agreeing to before saying yes.",
          "whyIncorrect": "A pitch that explains rules is a rulebook, not an invitation. It front-loads the complexity cost and creates an obstacle list. The pitch's only job is to generate a yes-to-trying; rule explanation belongs in the teach phase.",
          "remediationStrategy": "Have the learner write a pitch for a familiar game and time it. Any pitch over 90 seconds almost certainly includes rules. Ask them to cut everything not necessary to generate a yes.",
