  "glossary": [
    {
      "term": "mechanism",
      "definition": "The core action or system that players engage with during a game \u2014 what they are actually doing each turn. Mechanism is the strongest predictor of player enjoyment. Examples: deck-building, area control, social deduction, worker placement, tile drafting."
    },
    {
      "term": "game weight",
      "definition": "A measure of the cognitive complexity and rule density of a boardgame, typically rated on a 1\u20135 scale. Weight 1 = teachable in 2 minutes; weight 5 = requires substantial study. Weight is independent of game quality."
    },
    {
      "term": "gateway game",
      "definition": "A boardgame designed to introduce modern game mechanisms to new players, with meaningful decisions and satisfying learning arcs without overwhelming complexity. Examples: Ticket to Ride, Carcassonne, Pandemic."
    },
    {
      "term": "party game",
      "definition": "A boardgame designed primarily to generate social energy \u2014 laughter, conversation, group dynamics \u2014 rather than deep mechanism engagement. Examples: Codenames, Wavelength, Telestrations."
    },
    {
      "term": "mid-weight game",
      "definition": "A boardgame with genuine strategic depth requiring investment to learn but rewarding that investment with richer decisions. Weight approximately 2\u20133.5 on the 1\u20135 scale. Examples: Agricola, Viticulture, 7 Wonders, Scythe."
    },
    {
      "term": "reluctance type",
      "definition": "One of five diagnosable categories of resistance to playing boardgames: Complexity Aversion, Time Scarcity, Bad Prior Experience, Social Anxiety, and Identity Resistance. Each has specific observable signals and known remedies."
    },
    {
      "term": "complexity aversion",
      "definition": "A reluctance type in which a person fears the cognitive demands of learning or playing a game. Signals: 'I'm not good at these things.' Remedy: games with very short teach times, rules revealed during play."
    },
    {
      "term": "time scarcity",
      "definition": "A reluctance type in which a person believes they lack time for boardgame sessions. Can be genuine or a cover. Remedy: sub-30-minute games with explicit time promises. Diagnostic test: offer a 20-minute game and observe whether a new objection surfaces."
    },
    {
      "term": "bad prior experience",
      "definition": "A reluctance type driven by a specific negative memory \u2014 typically player elimination, excessive downtime, or a badly run teach. Remedy: briefly acknowledge, pivot immediately to a cooperative game with no elimination."
    },
    {
      "term": "social anxiety (boardgame context)",
      "definition": "A reluctance type in which a person fears public failure \u2014 making visible mistakes or being the weakest link. Remedy: games with hidden information, simultaneous play, or team structure that distributes responsibility."
    },
    {
      "term": "identity resistance",
      "definition": "A reluctance type in which playing boardgames conflicts with the person's self-concept. Remedy: detach the activity from the identity through familiar reference points and framing that avoids signalling hobby membership."
    },
    {
      "term": "stated objection",
      "definition": "The surface-level reason a person gives for not wanting to play boardgames. May differ from the underlying resistance. Common examples: 'I don't have time,' 'I'm not strategic,' 'It's not really my thing.'"
    },
    {
      "term": "underlying resistance",
      "definition": "The actual driver of reluctance to play boardgames, which may differ from the stated objection. Identified by the diagnostic test: offer something that removes the stated barrier; if a new objection surfaces, the first was a cover."
    },
    {
      "term": "framing",
      "definition": "A persuasion technique that selects which aspect of a game to lead with in a pitch, connecting the game to something the friend already cares about rather than leading with mechanism, weight, or theme."
    },
    {
      "term": "social proof",
      "definition": "A persuasion technique citing a specific person similar to the friend who tried the game and responded positively. More effective when the named person had the same resistance type as the friend being pitched."
    },
    {
      "term": "commitment threshold",
      "definition": "The perceived cost of agreeing to try a game. Lowering it means making the yes feel small and reversible \u2014 'we can try one 20-minute round and stop if you want.'"
    },
    {
      "term": "objection redirection",
      "definition": "A three-step technique for handling resistance: (1) Acknowledge the feeling, (2) Validate the general concern, (3) Redirect to a differentiating feature of the specific game that dissolves the concern."
    },
    {
      "term": "reactance",
      "definition": "A psychological phenomenon in which a person resists persuasion more strongly when they perceive their freedom to choose is being constrained. Enthusiast pressure triggers reactance; curiosity framing reduces it."
    },
    {
      "term": "60-second pitch",
      "definition": "A structured game invitation of under 60 seconds comprising five components: interest hook, plain-language action description, time/commitment frame, social proof or reassurance, and a direct low-threshold ask."
    },
    {
      "term": "FLGS",
      "definition": "Friendly Local Game Store. A specialist hobby game retailer that typically runs open game nights explicitly designed to welcome new players, often at low or no cost."
    },
    {
      "term": "Board Game Arena (BGA)",
      "definition": "A free-to-play browser-based platform hosting hundreds of boardgames with real-time and asynchronous play modes and an active global player community."
    },
    {
      "term": "BoardGameGeek (BGG)",
      "definition": "The primary online database and community hub for boardgame enthusiasts, containing game ratings, reviews, rules, regional guilds, and organised play communities."
    },
    {
      "term": "commitment device",
      "definition": "Any structure that makes it harder to back out of a future action. Examples: setting a specific next date before people leave, assigning bring-a-game roles, maintaining a shared game log, adopting a season model."
    },
    {
      "term": "next-time ritual",
      "definition": "The practice of securing a specific date and verbal commitment for the next game night session before attendees leave the current one. The single most effective habit-formation action available at the end of a session."
    },
    {
      "term": "Three Pillars (game night)",
      "definition": "The three structural requirements for a sustainable recurring game night: (1) a fixed, recurring time slot; (2) a clear host role with defined responsibilities; (3) game sequencing calibrated to the group's current state."
    },
    {
      "term": "quarterbacking",
      "definition": "In cooperative boardgames, the pattern where an experienced player directs other players' decisions rather than allowing them agency. Particularly harmful for socially anxious newcomers."
    },
    {
      "term": "deck-building",
      "definition": "A game mechanism in which players start with a weak deck and acquire cards over the game to build a stronger deck. Examples: Dominion, Star Realms."
    },
