              "blockId": "cb-01-01",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "LEARNING OBJECTIVES FOR THIS SECTION\n\n01-A \u2014 Classify any given boardgame into at least one mechanism category and justify the classification.\n01-B \u2014 Distinguish between game weight, play time, and theme as independent axes, and explain why conflating them leads to poor recommendations.\n01-C \u2014 Identify the player-count range and session-length category for at least six canonical gateway, mid-weight, and party games.\n01-D \u2014 Describe what a non-gamer is likely to perceive as appealing or threatening about a specific game based on its category profile.\n\nEstimated time: 40 minutes."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "cb-01-02",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "WHY YOUR VOCABULARY MATTERS BEFORE YOUR PITCH\n\nYou already know a lot about boardgames. That knowledge is an asset \u2014 but only if you can translate it. The problem most enthusiasts run into isn't a lack of passion; it's a lack of precision.\n\nWhen you tell a friend 'it's kind of like chess but more fun,' you've said nothing useful. When you tell them 'it's a 45-minute cooperative puzzle where everyone wins or loses together and nobody gets eliminated,' you've given them something they can evaluate.\n\nThis section builds the vocabulary the rest of the course depends on. Every tool in Sections 2, 3, and 4 requires you to reach back here. Think of it as calibrating your instruments before you start measuring."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "cb-01-03",
              "type": "image",
              "url": "https://cdn.convince-friends-boardgames.course/assets/s01/four-axis-radar.png",
              "altText": "A four-axis radar chart showing Weight, Play Time, Player Count, and Theme Intensity as independent dimensions, with four example games plotted: Codenames (low weight, low time, high player count, low theme), Twilight Imperium (high weight, high time, high player count, high theme), Agricola (high weight, medium time, low player count, medium theme), and Sushi Go (low weight, low time, medium player count, medium theme).",
              "captionOrTranscript": "MEDIA PLACEHOLDER \u2014 Diagram: Four-axis radar chart. Four axes radiating from centre: Weight (1\u20135), Play Time (15\u2013180+ min), Player Count (2\u201310+), Theme Intensity (abstract to highly thematic). Four games plotted as coloured polygon overlays showing how the same axis can score differently across games. Each axis label includes a brief definition. Caption: 'The four axes are independent \u2014 a game can be heavy and short, light and long, thematic and abstract. Changing one axis doesn't change the others.'"
            },
            {
              "blockId": "cb-01-04",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "THE FOUR AXES OF ANY BOARDGAME\n\nEvery boardgame can be described along four independent axes. Independent means changing one doesn't change the others \u2014 a game can be heavy and short, light and long, thematic and abstract. Conflating these axes is one of the most common mistakes enthusiasts make when recommending games.\n\nAXIS 1: MECHANISM \u2014 What are players actually doing?\nThis is the most predictive axis for whether someone will enjoy a game, yet it's the one enthusiasts mention least. The primary mechanisms include:\n\n\u2022 Area control \u2014 Players compete to dominate regions of a map. (Risk, Scythe)\n\u2022 Deck-building \u2014 Players start with a weak hand and acquire cards to build a stronger deck over time. (Dominion, Star Realms)\n\u2022 Cooperative \u2014 All players work together against the game system itself; everyone wins or loses as a team. (Pandemic, Hanabi)\n\u2022 Worker placement \u2014 Players place tokens on action spaces to claim resources or actions, and spaces are limited. (Agricola, Wingspan)\n\u2022 Drafting \u2014 Players select cards or tiles from a shared pool, passing the remainder to the next player. (7 Wonders, Sushi Go)\n\u2022 Social deduction \u2014 Players have hidden roles and must identify who is lying. (The Resistance, Secret Hitler)\n\u2022 Route building \u2014 Players construct networks \u2014 roads, train lines \u2014 to score points. (Ticket to Ride, Carcassonne)\n\nMost games combine two or more mechanisms. Wingspan is a card-drafting engine-builder. Viticulture combines worker placement with hand management. For pitching purposes, identify the primary mechanism \u2014 the one that drives most decisions.\n\nAXIS 2: WEIGHT (COMPLEXITY)\nWeight is the cognitive load a game demands, rated on a 1\u20135 scale popularised by BoardGameGeek. A weight-1 game (Sushi Go) can be explained in two minutes. A weight-4 game (Arkham Horror: The Card Game) may require a 20-page rulebook and tracking multiple overlapping systems.\n\nCritical point: weight is not quality. Codenames is a weight-1.5 game and one of the most celebrated designs of the past decade. Mage Knight is a weight-4.8 game many players find too demanding. The right weight is the weight that matches your audience.\n\nAXIS 3: PLAY TIME\nUse actual play time, not box-stated time. Box times are optimistic. Rule of thumb: multiply box-stated time by 1.3 for experienced players, and by 1.75 for groups that include new players. A '30-minute' game with first-timers often takes 45\u201350 minutes.\n\nAXIS 4: PLAYER COUNT\nGames have an optimal count within a listed range. Ticket to Ride lists 2\u20135 but plays best at 3\u20134. The Resistance lists 5\u201310 and is genuinely poor with fewer than 5. Recommending a game without knowing the likely group size is like recommending a recipe without checking how many people are eating."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "cb-01-05",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "THE GATEWAY / MID-WEIGHT / PARTY DISTINCTION\n\nThree categories that are frequently confused \u2014 and the confusion leads to the wrong game for the wrong moment.\n\nGATEWAY GAMES are designed to introduce genuine boardgame mechanisms to players who haven't encountered them before. They have meaningful decisions, real rule structures, and a satisfying arc of learning. The experience is: 'I learned something, I made choices, and those choices mattered.' Examples: Ticket to Ride, Carcassonne, Pandemic.\n\nPARTY GAMES are designed primarily to generate social energy \u2014 laughter, conversation, and group dynamics. The mechanism is often thin or irrelevant; the point is the interaction. The experience is: 'That was hilarious, and it doesn't really matter who won.' Examples: Codenames, Wavelength, Just One, Telestrations.\n\nMID-WEIGHT GAMES have genuine strategic depth and require investment to learn, but reward that investment with richer decisions and longer engagement. Examples: Agricola, Viticulture, Scythe, 7 Wonders.\n\nWhy does this distinction matter? Because the wrong recommendation is worse than no recommendation. A friend who agreed to 'a quick party game' and ended up spending three hours learning Agricola won't trust your recommendations again. A friend who enjoys deep strategy but was offered Codenames may write off boardgames as shallow. The category shapes the expectation, and the expectation shapes the experience."
            },
