              "captionOrTranscript": "MEDIA PLACEHOLDER \u2014 Video (2\u20133 minutes): Presenter holds the Azul box and works through the four-axis classification aloud. Script outline: (1) Show the box \u2014 'This is Azul. Let's classify it.' (2) Mechanism: 'Players are picking tiles from a central market and placing them in patterns on their boards. That's drafting plus pattern-building.' (3) Weight: 'The rules fit on two pages. Five-minute teach time. But there's genuine tactical depth \u2014 weight about 1.8.' (4) Play time: 'Box says 30\u201345 minutes. Accurate for this one.' (5) Player count: '2\u20134, works well at all counts, best at 2 or 3.' (6) Conclude by translating to plain language: 'For a newcomer: You pick colourful tiles from a shared market and build a mosaic. Teaches in five minutes, plays in half an hour.' Show the contrast between the internal classification (mechanism, weight score) and the plain-language output."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "cb-01-08",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "WHAT NON-GAMERS FEAR \u2014 AND WHAT THEY WANT\n\nThis bridges Objective 01-D and begins building your audience-reading skills for Section 2.\n\nWhen a non-gamer looks at a boardgame invitation, their threat-detection system is scanning for:\n\n\u2022 'Will I look stupid?' \u2014 Long teach times and complex rules signal high risk of public failure in front of friends.\n\u2022 'Will I be trapped?' \u2014 Long play times feel like commitments they can't exit gracefully once they've started.\n\u2022 'Is this for those people?' \u2014 Elaborate fantasy artwork and niche references signal 'this is a club I don't belong to.'\n\u2022 'Will I ruin it for everyone?' \u2014 Cooperative games with experienced players can feel like being the weakest link.\n\nAnd what draws them in:\n\n\u2022 Social interaction \u2014 Anything that produces conversation, laughter, or shared moments.\n\u2022 Low stakes \u2014 Short games where a bad result costs little time or social capital.\n\u2022 Familiar reference points \u2014 'It's like [something they already know]' is a powerful on-ramp.\n\u2022 Visible progress \u2014 Games where something changes on the table every turn satisfy the need to feel something is happening.\n\nYour job in Section 1 is to build a mental map precise enough that you can predict which of these fears a specific game will trigger \u2014 and which draws it will create. That prediction is the foundation of everything in Sections 2, 3, and 4."
            },
