          "contentBlocks": [
            {
              "blockId": "cb-02-01",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "LEARNING OBJECTIVES FOR THIS SECTION\n\n02-A \u2014 Distinguish between at least five distinct reluctance types and identify their observable signals.\n02-B \u2014 Match a game recommendation to a specific reluctance profile using mechanism and social fit criteria.\n02-C \u2014 Identify when a stated objection differs from underlying resistance and explain why the gap matters.\n\nEstimated time: 40 minutes.\n\nNOTE: This section builds directly on Section 1. You will need the four-axis framework (mechanism, weight, play time, player count) to select appropriate games for each reluctance type. If those terms feel unfamiliar, revisit Section 1 before continuing."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "cb-02-02",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "THE DIAGNOSTIC BEFORE THE PRESCRIPTION\n\nImagine visiting a doctor who prescribes medication before asking about your symptoms. That's exactly what most enthusiasts do when they lead with a game recommendation before understanding why their friend is hesitant.\n\nReluctance is almost never general. 'I don't like boardgames' is the surface. Underneath, there is almost always something specific: a bad past experience, a fear of looking confused, a genuine time constraint, or an identity conflict about what kind of person plays boardgames.\n\nYour job in this section is to become a better diagnostician \u2014 to read the signals accurately before you reach for a solution. This matters because the wrong remedy for the wrong resistance type doesn't just fail; it makes the next invitation harder.\n\nThis is also where Section 1's game taxonomy becomes a practical tool. You need to know the full landscape of game types to match the right game to the right resistance. If you only know three games well, you have only three solutions available \u2014 and you'll be tempted to fit every person to one of those three, which is a hammer looking for nails."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "cb-02-03",
              "type": "image",
              "url": "https://cdn.convince-friends-boardgames.course/assets/s02/reluctance-type-cards.png",
              "altText": "Five reluctance type cards arranged in a grid, each showing type name, observable signal, underlying fear, wrong response, and right response",
              "captionOrTranscript": "MEDIA PLACEHOLDER \u2014 Diagram: Five cards arranged in a 2x3 grid (2 columns, 3 rows, fifth card centred on last row). Each card has a distinct background colour and contains five labelled fields: TYPE NAME (large, bold), OBSERVABLE SIGNAL (what they actually say or do), UNDERLYING FEAR (the real issue), WRONG RESPONSE (what most enthusiasts do), RIGHT RESPONSE (what works). Cards: Type 1 Complexity Aversion (blue), Type 2 Time Scarcity (green), Type 3 Bad Prior Experience (orange), Type 4 Social Anxiety (purple), Type 5 Identity Resistance (red). Visual style: clean card design, high contrast, suitable for use as a reference graphic learners can return to."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "cb-02-04",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "THE FIVE RELUCTANCE TYPES\n\nThese five types account for the vast majority of real-world resistance to playing boardgames. Most friends exhibit one primary type; many show signals of a secondary type. Your job is to identify the primary driver \u2014 the one that, if addressed, would most likely produce a yes.\n\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nTYPE 1: COMPLEXITY AVERSION\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nWhat they say: 'I'm not good at these kinds of games.' / 'It looks really complicated.' / 'I never know what I'm supposed to be doing.'\n\nWhat's really happening: They have been burned by a game where they felt confused for most of the session \u2014 typically an over-explained, rule-heavy game introduced badly. They are protecting themselves from repeating that experience.\n\nWrong response: Explaining the full ruleset of your game to show them it's 'not that complex, really.' More explanation confirms the threat. The friend hears 'here is a list of everything you have to remember' and their anxiety increases, not decreases.\n\nRight response: Offer a game with a 3-minute teach time. Start playing immediately, revealing rules only as they become needed. The feeling of competence during the first few turns is more persuasive than any pre-game description.\n\nGame profile (using Section 1 axes): Weight 1\u20132. Mechanisms that are immediately legible from the table \u2014 drafting, route-building, pattern-building. Avoid games with many exception cases or overlapping systems.\nExamples: Sushi Go! (weight 1.4, 15\u201320 min), Azul (weight 1.8, 30\u201345 min), Ticket to Ride (weight 1.9, 45\u201375 min).\n\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nTYPE 2: TIME SCARCITY\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nWhat they say: 'I'd love to, but we never have time for long games.' / 'Can we play something quick?'\n\nWhat's really happening: Sometimes this is true \u2014 they genuinely have limited windows. But time scarcity is also the most socially acceptable excuse in the English language, which means it frequently covers something else (usually Type 1 or Type 5). You can distinguish genuine from cover by how they respond when you offer a 20-minute game: enthusiastic acceptance means genuine; a new objection means cover.\n\nWrong response: Agreeing to a 'quick' game that actually runs 60 minutes with new players. Box times are optimistic. If you promised 30 minutes and delivered 90, you have damaged trust and made the next invitation harder.\n\nRight response: Offer explicitly short games and deliver precisely on the time promise. Frame the commitment as minimal and reversible: 'We can stop after one round if you're not into it.'\n\nGame profile: Sub-30-minute actual play time. High replayability in short bursts. Avoid games with long setup.\nExamples: Coup (15 min), Love Letter (20 min), Skull (20 min), Sushi Go! (15\u201320 min).\n\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nTYPE 3: BAD PRIOR EXPERIENCE\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nWhat they say: 'I played Monopoly as a kid and hated it.' / 'We played something at a party and I had nothing to do for an hour.' / 'The last time someone taught me rules it took 45 minutes.'\n\nWhat's really happening: They have a concrete negative memory attached to boardgames. Usually Monopoly (player elimination, long downtime, luck-heavy endgame) or a game that was taught badly by someone who confused pitch with teach. They have generalised from that experience to 'boardgames are not for me.'\n\nWrong response: Defending boardgames as a category ('but modern games are nothing like Monopoly!') or arguing them out of their memory. You cannot talk someone out of a bad experience. The argument creates resistance; the experience resolves it.\n\nRight response: Acknowledge the experience briefly ('Yeah, Monopoly is a rough introduction'), pivot immediately to contrast ('What I want to show you is completely different'), and then deliver a game that is, in fact, completely different: short, cooperative, no player elimination.\n\nGame profile: Cooperative mechanism removes the threat of losing to another person. Short, low weight. Zero player elimination. Clear win/loss endpoint as a team.\nExamples: The Crew (20\u201330 min per mission), Hanabi (25 min), Pandemic (45\u201360 min \u2014 higher time offset by cooperative warmth).\n\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nTYPE 4: SOCIAL ANXIETY\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nWhat they say: 'I don't want to slow everyone down.' / 'I'm always the one who messes up.' / 'I hate being put on the spot.' / They keep finding reasons not to commit to a specific night.\n\nWhat's really happening: They are afraid of public failure \u2014 making a bad move everyone can see, asking a question that reveals confusion, or being the weakest link in a group where others are more experienced. This is the deepest and most fragile resistance type.\n\nWrong response: Cooperative games where experienced players 'helpfully' direct the anxious person's decisions. This is called quarterbacking in the hobby, and it makes social anxiety dramatically worse: the person is now visibly following instructions rather than making choices, which is more exposing, not less.\n\nRight response: Games with hidden information (no one sees your hand or strategy), low weight (so the failure floor is low), and either simultaneous play or very short turns (minimising the 'spotlight' period). Critically: brief the experienced players before the session about not directing others.\n\nGame profile: Hidden information so failures are not public. Low weight, low decision complexity per turn. Avoid any game where other players can observe your choices as you make them.\nExamples: Codenames (team structure distributes responsibility), Just One (simultaneous play), Wavelength (no objectively wrong answers).\n\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nTYPE 5: IDENTITY RESISTANCE\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nWhat they say: 'That's not really my thing.' / 'I'm not a gamer.' / 'This feels very nerdy.' / They associate boardgames with a social group they don't identify with.\n\nWhat's really happening: This isn't about the game \u2014 it is about identity. Playing boardgames feels like joining a tribe they don't belong to. The game is a proxy for 'I don't want to be that kind of person.' This is the hardest resistance type and cannot be addressed through game mechanics alone.\n\nWrong response: More enthusiasm for the hobby. Enthusiast energy can confirm their suspicion that this is 'a boardgame people thing,' and they are not boardgame people.\n\nRight response: Detach the activity from the identity. Frame the game through a lens they already identify with \u2014 a strategy challenge, a conversation game, a wine night activity. The goal is to help them have the experience before they have decided what it means about them.\n\nGame profile: High social energy, familiar reference points, plausible deniability ('it's more of a party game'). Avoid anything that looks unmistakably like 'a boardgame' on the box.\nExamples: Wavelength (feels like a conversation game), Codenames (feels like a word game), Dixit (feels like an art activity), Skull (feels like a bar game)."
            }
