              "type": "text",
              "content": "STATED OBJECTION VS. UNDERLYING RESISTANCE\n\nObjective 02-C is where most persuasion attempts fail. The stated objection \u2014 what a friend says when they decline \u2014 is often not the real barrier. Addressing the stated objection produces a second objection, not a yes. Addressing the underlying resistance produces a yes.\n\nHere is the map of the most common stated-to-underlying translations:\n\n'I don't have time.'\n\u2192 Possible underlying: Time Scarcity (genuine) / Social Anxiety (escape route) / Bad Prior Experience (expects it to drag on)\n\n'I'm not very strategic.'\n\u2192 Possible underlying: Complexity Aversion / Social Anxiety (fear of visible failure)\n\n'It's not really my thing.'\n\u2192 Possible underlying: Identity Resistance / Bad Prior Experience\n\n'Maybe next time.'\n\u2192 Possible underlying: Social Anxiety (avoidance without clear reason) / genuine scheduling conflict\n\n'I'll just watch.'\n\u2192 Possible underlying: Social Anxiety (doesn't want to be put on the spot) / Bad Prior Experience (been excluded mid-game before)\n\nNone of these mappings are certain \u2014 they are starting hypotheses to test."
