              "content": "LEARNING OBJECTIVES FOR THIS SECTION\n\n03-A \u2014 Construct a game pitch of under 60 seconds using the five-component structure, framing in the friend's terms rather than the game's mechanics.\n03-B \u2014 Apply at least two persuasion principles in a game invitation scenario, naming the technique used.\n03-C \u2014 Demonstrate the three-step objection-redirection sequence (acknowledge, validate, redirect).\n03-D \u2014 Evaluate an enthusiasm-driven vs. a curiosity-framed pitch and explain which is more effective and why.\n\nEstimated time: 55 minutes.\n\nIMPORTANT: This section builds on both Section 1 and Section 2. You will need your game taxonomy knowledge (Section 1) to describe games accurately in plain language, and your diagnosis of the friend's resistance type (Section 2) to choose the right interest hook and social proof. If either of those feels shaky, revisit those sections before continuing."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "cb-03-02",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "WHAT A PITCH IS \u2014 AND ISN'T\n\nA pitch is not a tutorial. It is not a defence of boardgaming as a hobby. It is not an opportunity to share everything you love about a game.\n\nA pitch has exactly one job: generate a 'yes, I'll try it.' That's it. Everything else \u2014 rules, strategy tips, expansion recommendations \u2014 comes after the yes, or never at all. The moment you conflate pitch with teach, you have written a rulebook instead of an invitation.\n\nThis matters because most enthusiasts, when excited about a game, naturally default to explaining it. They believe that clarity is persuasive. It isn't \u2014 not at this stage. What is persuasive is relevance: making the other person feel that this experience was designed for them, or at least is safe for them to try.\n\nSection 2 gave you the diagnostic tools to understand who you are talking to. This section gives you the rhetorical tools to move them. But notice the dependency: the best pitch in the world, aimed at the wrong resistance type, will fail. You need both the diagnosis and the pitch \u2014 and in that order."
