              "blockId": "cb-03-04",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "THE FIVE PERSUASION PRINCIPLES\n\nThese principles come from social psychology and rhetoric applied to a specific context: low-stakes social invitations. They are not manipulation \u2014 they are communication structures that reduce friction, clarify value, and make it easier for someone to say yes to something they might actually enjoy.\n\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nPRINCIPLE 1: FRAMING\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nFraming is choosing which aspect of something to lead with. The same game can be described accurately in multiple ways \u2014 and the framing you choose determines what the listener imagines.\n\nBland frame: 'It's a deck-building game where you acquire cards and optimise your engine.'\nInterest-matched frame: 'It's like building a startup from scratch \u2014 you start with almost nothing and slowly acquire resources until you're running a machine.'\n\nNeither is false. But only the second connects to something the listener already has a feeling about.\n\nThe rule: Lead with what it feels like, not what it is. 'What it is' is mechanism \u2014 your Section 1 knowledge. 'What it feels like' is the experiential translation of that mechanism into human terms your friend already understands.\n\nThis is where Section 1 and Section 2 converge: you use your game taxonomy knowledge to identify the core mechanism, and your audience diagnosis to choose which experiential frame will resonate with this specific person.\n\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nPRINCIPLE 2: SOCIAL PROOF\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nPeople are more likely to try something when they know others like them have tried it and survived. This is especially powerful for skeptics.\n\nLess effective: 'I really love this game.'\nMore effective: 'My partner had zero interest in boardgames and this was the first one she actually asked to play again.'\n\nThe difference: the first is your opinion. The second is evidence about someone similar to your friend.\n\nBe specific. 'My mum plays it' beats 'anyone can play it.' 'My friend who hates strategy games loved it' beats 'even non-gamers enjoy it.' Name the person, name their prior resistance, name the outcome. The more precisely the named person mirrors your friend's resistance type, the more persuasive the proof.\n\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nPRINCIPLE 3: LOWERING THE COMMITMENT THRESHOLD\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nThe biggest barrier to a first yes is perceived commitment. If trying the game feels permanent, expensive in time, or long, people will protect themselves by saying no.\n\nLower the threshold at every opportunity:\n\u2022 'We can just try one round \u2014 if you're not into it after 20 minutes, we stop.'\n\u2022 'It only takes five minutes to explain \u2014 you can decide whether you want to play after you hear it.'\n\u2022 'You're not committing to anything \u2014 just try it once.'\n\nEach of these shrinks the cost of saying yes. The friend isn't agreeing to 'become a boardgame person' \u2014 they're agreeing to a 20-minute experiment with a clear exit.\n\nThe question to ask yourself: what is the smallest possible commitment they could make that would still result in them playing? Offer that.\n\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nPRINCIPLE 4: LOSS AVERSION (LIGHT TOUCH)\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nLoss aversion \u2014 the tendency to weigh potential losses more heavily than equivalent gains \u2014 can be used gently and honestly.\n\nWorks: 'Last time we played this without you, you were the only one who missed it.'\nWorks: 'Everyone who's played it says it was the best game they played that month.'\nDamages trust: 'This is literally the best game ever made.' Overstating the claim burns your credibility for future invitations. Use this principle sparingly \u2014 as a light nudge at the end of a pitch, not the entire strategy.\n\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nPRINCIPLE 5: OBJECTION REDIRECTION (NOT REFUTATION)\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nWhen someone objects, the instinctive response is to refute \u2014 to show they are wrong. This almost always backfires. Refutation creates a debate, and debates produce defensiveness, not openness.\n\nRedirection: acknowledge the objection, absorb it, and redirect toward a positive.\n\nThe three-step structure:\n1. ACKNOWLEDGE \u2014 'Yeah, I get that.'\n2. VALIDATE the feeling, not the conclusion \u2014 'A lot of games are like that.'\n3. REDIRECT \u2014 'This one is specifically designed not to be.'\n\nExample:\nFriend: 'I just find these games really stressful.'\nRefutation (wrong): 'It's not stressful at all! It's really fun and light.'\nRedirection (right): 'Yeah, some games are genuinely stressful \u2014 especially competitive ones where every mistake is visible. This one is cooperative, so the only people you're playing against are yourselves. The tension, if anything, is like a puzzle you're solving together.'\n\nNotice that the redirection does not argue with the feeling. It changes what the feeling is attached to."
            },
