            {
              "blockId": "cb-03-06",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "THE 60-SECOND PITCH STRUCTURE\n\nHere is a reusable skeleton. Every component is required. The entire pitch should run under 60 seconds when delivered aloud \u2014 time yourself.\n\n[INTEREST HOOK] \u2014 One sentence connecting to something your friend already cares about. This comes from your Section 2 diagnosis of their interests and resistance type.\n\n[WHAT YOU DO] \u2014 One sentence describing the primary action in plain language. No mechanism names, no BGG vocabulary, no jargon. This comes from your Section 1 four-axis classification translated into human terms.\n\n[TIME / COMMITMENT FRAME] \u2014 One sentence establishing that this is a small and reversible investment.\n\n[SOCIAL PROOF OR REASSURANCE] \u2014 One sentence about a specific person like them who enjoyed it, or a direct reassurance targeting the resistance type you diagnosed.\n\n[ASK] \u2014 One direct, specific, low-threshold request. 'Want to try one round?' Not 'Do you want to play sometime?' \u2014 a specific, immediate ask.\n\nA fifth component (time frame) is occasionally folded into the ask: 'Want to try one 20-minute round?' That is acceptable \u2014 the point is that every component is present, not that each gets exactly one sentence."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "cb-03-07",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "ENTHUSIASM VS. CURIOSITY FRAMING\n\nThis is the most important contrast in the section. Read both versions of the same pitch carefully.\n\nGame: Pandemic. Friend: Type 3 (Bad Prior Experience). Same game, same friend, two different approaches.\n\nVERSION A \u2014 ENTHUSIASM-DRIVEN:\n'Oh my god, you have to play Pandemic \u2014 it's SO GOOD. I've played it probably 20 times and it never gets old. The mechanics are brilliant, it's cooperative so you all win or lose together, and the tension builds so perfectly toward the end. I seriously think it might be the best gateway cooperative game ever designed. You're going to love it.'\n\nVERSION B \u2014 CURIOSITY-FRAMED:\n'Have you ever played a game where everyone is on the same team? I was skeptical too, but this one works really differently from what you're probably imagining. You're trying to stop disease outbreaks together, and the whole thing takes under an hour. Want to see how it works?'\n\nWHY VERSION B IS MORE EFFECTIVE:\n\nVersion A makes the game about you \u2014 your love, your play count, your judgment. The friend now faces social pressure: either match your enthusiasm (unlikely for a Type 3 resister) or deflate it by being unimpressed. Version A also front-loads the friend's cost: 20+ plays, 'best ever made' \u2014 these are signals of high stakes, not low ones. For a Type 3 resister who had a bad experience before, 'you're going to love it' is a threat, not a promise.\n\nVersion B makes the game about them \u2014 their experience, their curiosity, their choice. It acknowledges prior skepticism ('I was skeptical too'), describes the mechanism in one plain sentence, gives a concrete time commitment, and ends with an open-ended ask rather than a demand to feel the same way you do.\n\nThe underlying principle is reactance: a psychological phenomenon in which people resist persuasion more strongly when they perceive their freedom to choose is being constrained. Enthusiast pressure feels like constraint. Curiosity-framing feels like an open door.\n\nThis is not about being less passionate. It is about directing your passion toward the friend's experience rather than your own."
