          "contentBlocks": [
            {
              "blockId": "cb-04-01",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "LEARNING OBJECTIVES FOR THIS SECTION\n\n04-A \u2014 Design a game night structure suited to a specific group profile.\n04-B \u2014 Identify at least two commitment devices and select the most appropriate for a given group's stage.\n04-C \u2014 Evaluate the tradeoffs of at least three community-finding channels against your constraints.\n04-D \u2014 Construct a 30-day integration plan for entering a chosen community.\n\nEstimated time: 45 minutes.\n\nTHIS IS THE CAPSTONE SECTION. It draws on everything you have built:\n\u2022 Section 1 (game taxonomy): which games to select and sequence by weight and play time.\n\u2022 Section 2 (audience reading): how to profile the group and manage newcomers' resistance types.\n\u2022 Section 3 (pitch and persuasion): how to make first contact with a new community and secure commitment after a session.\n\nIf any of those sections feel uncertain, revisit them before continuing \u2014 you will need them here."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "cb-04-02",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "FROM THE FIRST YES TO THE FIFTH GAME NIGHT\n\nGetting someone to the table once is a persuasion problem \u2014 you solved that in Section 3. Getting them back is a design problem. These require different skills, and most enthusiasts only learn the first one.\n\nThe distinction matters because a positive first session creates inclination, not routine. Routine requires structure: a recurring time, a clear social role, and gradually increasing investment from the players themselves. Without that structure, even a session where everyone has a great time tends to dissolve into 'we should definitely do that again' \u2014 and then does not happen again.\n\nThis section gives you the design vocabulary for building the structure that turns a first session into a tenth.\n\nThe same skills also apply beyond your existing friend group. When friends remain unpersuaded despite your best efforts \u2014 which happens, and is not a failure \u2014 your game taxonomy fluency, audience diagnosis, and pitch skills transfer directly to finding new players. The second half of this section covers that."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "cb-04-03",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "THE THREE PILLARS OF A SUSTAINABLE GAME NIGHT\n\nA game night that persists past the third session reliably has three structural features. A game night missing any one of them reliably does not.\n\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nPILLAR 1: A FIXED, RECURRING TIME\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n'Let's do it again sometime' does not happen. 'First Saturday of the month, 6pm' does.\n\nThe difference is not motivation \u2014 it is friction. A fixed time removes the weekly negotiation cost (Who is free? When? Where?) and lets attendees plan around it. The specific cadence matters less than the consistency. Monthly works for busy adults with full calendars; biweekly works for tighter groups with more flexibility. Weekly is sustainable only for very committed groups with few competing social obligations.\n\nThe fixed time is also a social signal: this is a real thing, not a vague intention. People take it more seriously when it is scheduled, the same way a standing meeting feels more real than 'let's catch up soon.'\n\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nPILLAR 2: A CLEAR HOST ROLE\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nSomeone must own the logistics: the location, the game selection shortlist, the food and drink arrangement, and the reminder message two days before. This does not have to be the same person every session \u2014 the host role can rotate \u2014 but it must be a named person for each session.\n\nDistributed ownership sounds democratic and produces nothing. 'Everyone can bring a game' means no one is certain a game will be there. 'Everyone can sort food' means someone buys crisps at the last minute and someone else forgot entirely. Clarity of ownership, even informal, is what separates events that happen from events that were going to happen.\n\nAs the group matures (Sessions 4\u20138 and beyond), the host role can be shared or rotated. In the early phase \u2014 when the habit is not yet formed \u2014 one person taking clear ownership dramatically increases the probability of sessions two and three occurring.\n\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nPILLAR 3: GAME SEQUENCING MATCHED TO THE GROUP'S PHASE\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nNot every session should have the same structure. The right game selection depends on which phase the group is in.\n\nSESSIONS 1\u20133 (HABIT FORMATION PHASE): The most fragile period. Play only games you know will land \u2014 not your personal favourites, but the games with the highest positive reaction rate across diverse player types. Length is critical: end every session while people still want more. Stop before exhaustion.\n\nRule for newcomers: Opener (15\u201320 min, light, social) \u2192 Main event (45\u201360 min maximum, cooperative or semi-cooperative to reduce interpersonal friction) \u2192 Optional closer (15 min, high energy). Using Section 1 axes: opener at weight 1\u20131.5, main event at weight 1.5\u20132.5, closer at weight 1\u20131.5.\n\nSESSIONS 4\u20138 (INVESTMENT PHASE): Regulars are forming. They now have shared references, in-jokes, and a sense of 'our group.' Introduce slightly heavier games. Begin sharing game curation responsibility \u2014 ask regulars to suggest the opener or bring a candidate for the main event. This is the first moment where Pillar 2 (host ownership) can begin to distribute.\n\nSESSIONS 9+ (ESTABLISHED PHASE): The group has an identity. You can introduce campaign games requiring multiple sessions, tackle longer heavier games with confidence, and plan themed evenings. The structure that was essential in phase one can relax without the group dissolving."
            },
