              "captionOrTranscript": "MEDIA PLACEHOLDER \u2014 Diagram: Horizontal timeline of a 3-hour game night session. Time blocks from left to right: 6:00\u20136:20 (Arrival and food \u2014 informal, no rules); 6:20\u20136:45 (Opener \u2014 light, 15\u201320 min game, familiar for regulars, low-stakes for newcomers \u2014 label: 'Establishes ritual, signals start'); 6:45\u20138:15 (Main event \u2014 mid-weight cooperative, 60\u201375 min \u2014 label: 'Core experience, chosen by headcount'); 8:15\u20138:40 (Closer \u2014 short, high-energy, 15\u201320 min \u2014 label: 'Ends on a peak'); 8:40\u20138:45 ('Next Time' Moment \u2014 verbal date commitment, calendar invite \u2014 label: 'This is the habit-forming step'). Each block has a purpose label beneath it in italics. Colour gradient from warm (arrival) to peak (closer) to anchoring (next time). Style: clean, readable, could function as a reference card."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "cb-04-05",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "THE 'NEXT TIME' RITUAL\n\nThe single most effective action at the end of any game night session is to set the next specific date before anyone leaves.\n\nNot 'we should do this again soon.' A specific date. 'Same time, four weeks from now \u2014 does Saturday the 15th work for everyone?' Get a verbal yes from everyone present before they walk out the door. A calendar invite sent immediately after reinforces but does not replace the in-person commitment.\n\nWhy does this work? Two reasons:\n\n1. TIMING: The commitment is made at the peak of positive emotion \u2014 people are still in the warmth of the session, laughing, energised. The social cost of saying 'actually, I can't' is highest at this moment. Every day that passes after the session ends, that social cost drops, and the probability of someone bailing increases.\n\n2. SPECIFICITY: A specific date with a verbal agreement creates a social contract that 'we should do this again' does not. Breaking a named commitment requires an active decision and explanation. Drifting away from a vague intention requires no decision at all.\n\nThis is the bridge between a positive experience and a recurring habit. Without it, even the best first session tends not to produce a second one."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "cb-04-06",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "COMMITMENT DEVICES AND SOCIAL ACCOUNTABILITY\n\nA commitment device is any structure that makes it harder to back out of a future action. Social accountability is the specific variety that uses peer relationships to do the enforcing.\n\nHere are the four most practical commitment devices for a game night group, ordered from simplest to most structured:\n\nDEVICE 1: THE GROUP CHAT\nCreate a dedicated group chat for game night \u2014 separate from any existing friend-group chats. This creates an identity ('Game Night People') and a channel where attendance confirmations, game suggestions, and in-jokes accumulate between sessions. The social cost of dropping out increases when dropping out means going silent in a chat where everyone else is visibly engaged.\nSetup effort: Low. Effectiveness for new groups: High. Best for: any group.\n\nDEVICE 2: BRING-A-GAME OWNERSHIP\nAssign each regular a specific role for the next session: 'You are bringing the opener,' 'You are on dessert,' 'You are suggesting the main event.' This distributes investment and creates named accountability. Someone who has agreed to bring a specific game is significantly more likely to show up than someone who has simply said yes.\nSetup effort: Low. Effectiveness for new groups: High. Best for: groups with 3\u20136 people who need to feel ownership.\n\nDEVICE 3: THE RUNNING RECORD\nMaintain a shared log of games played, scores, and memorable moments \u2014 a Google Sheet works perfectly. This creates a shared history with value that would be lost if game night ended: a mild but genuine loss-aversion mechanism. Looking back at ten sessions of memories makes future cancellation feel like a loss, not just an inconvenience.\nSetup effort: Medium. Effectiveness for established groups: Very high. Best for: groups past session 4.\n\nDEVICE 4: THE SEASON MODEL\nFor groups that struggle with consistency, propose a bounded commitment: 'Let us commit to six sessions over the next three months. At the end, we evaluate together and decide whether to continue.' A finite, scoped commitment is significantly easier to make than an open-ended one. The season structure also creates a natural renewal conversation \u2014 which tends to be a yes, once the group has already established a shared history.\nSetup effort: Low. Effectiveness for new or struggling groups: High. Best for: groups where 'forever' feels overwhelming."
            },
