          "contentBlocks": [
            {
              "blockId": "cb-04-08",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "WHEN YOUR FRIENDS WON'T COME AROUND\n\nSome friends, despite your best diagnostic and pitching work, will not become game night regulars. Some will not try at all. This is not a failure \u2014 boardgames are not for everyone \u2014 and the skills you have built in this course are most effective when used to find genuine interest rather than override genuine disinterest.\n\nThe good news: there are many people who want to play boardgames and have no one to play with. They are actively looking for you. Your game taxonomy fluency, your ability to read a room, and your pitch skills transfer directly to finding them and making first contact.\n\nThis experience covers the five channels for finding boardgame communities and a practical 30-day integration plan for entering one."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "cb-04-09",
              "type": "image",
              "url": "https://cdn.convince-friends-boardgames.course/assets/s04/community-channels-map.png",
              "altText": "A visual map showing five community-finding channels radiating from a central figure, each annotated with distance, cost, social density, and entry barrier",
              "captionOrTranscript": "MEDIA PLACEHOLDER \u2014 Diagram: Central figure labelled 'You' with five channels radiating outward like spokes. Each channel is a labelled circle with four annotation tags beneath it: Distance (Local / Online), Cost (Free / Low / High), Social Density (Small group / Large group), Entry Barrier (Low / Medium / High). Channels: FLGS Game Nights (Local, Free\u2013Low, Small group, Low); BGG Local Guilds (Local, Free, Small\u2013medium group, Medium); Meetup.com / Facebook Groups (Local/online, Free, Variable, Low\u2013Medium); Online Platforms \u2014 BGA / TTS (Online, Free\u2013Low, Large global, Low); Conventions (Local travel required, High, Large group, Low once there). Style: clean radial layout, each channel in a distinct colour, annotation tags in small italic text."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "cb-04-10",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "THE FIVE COMMUNITY CHANNELS\n\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nCHANNEL 1: FRIENDLY LOCAL GAME STORE (FLGS) GAME NIGHTS\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nWhat it is: Most hobby game stores run regular open game nights \u2014 typically weekly, sometimes free, sometimes with a small cover charge. Staff are almost always welcoming. Tables, demo copies, and a 'newcomers welcome' social norm are built in.\n\nWho it is for: Anyone who wants in-person play, does not know anyone in the local hobby community, and wants a structured environment where showing up alone is not awkward. The lowest-friction entry point to in-person play.\n\nPrimary tradeoff: Highly geography-dependent. Dense urban areas have multiple FLGS; rural areas may have none. Check BGG's store locator before concluding one doesn't exist nearby.\n\nMisconception to address: FLGS game nights are not only for purchasing games. The event is often deliberate loss-leading for the store \u2014 they want you there to build community. You can attend without buying anything.\n\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nCHANNEL 2: BOARDGAMEGEEK LOCAL GUILDS\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nWhat it is: BGG has a 'guilds' feature with thousands of regional groups, searchable by location. Many run their own events in homes, pubs, or community spaces \u2014 independent of any game store.\n\nWho it is for: Learners in areas without a good FLGS, or those who want a more established community of enthusiasts rather than a drop-in store event.\n\nPrimary tradeoff: Requires more initiative to enter. These are established communities, not structured newcomer events. Your Section 1 game knowledge and Section 3 framing skills are directly applicable to your first-contact post.\n\nFirst-contact strategy (applying Section 3): Post a brief introduction \u2014 your location, three games you enjoy that span the weight range (use your Section 1 taxonomy to choose representative examples), and what you are looking for. This is a pitch to a community, not a friend: curiosity-framed, specific, low-threshold.\n\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nCHANNEL 3: MEETUP.COM AND FACEBOOK GROUPS\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nWhat it is: General event platforms hosting hobby-organised boardgame meetups. More variable in quality and commitment than FLGS events, but often geographically broader.\n\nWho it is for: Learners who prefer the neutrality of a general platform over approaching a specialist store or niche forum. Lower initial intimidation for those still building confidence.\n\nPrimary tradeoff: Consistency and quality vary significantly. Some groups are active communities; others are dormant. Attend one session before investing significant social capital.\n\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nCHANNEL 4: ONLINE PLATFORMS\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nWhat they are: Board Game Arena (BGA) is a free browser platform with hundreds of games, real-time and asynchronous play modes, and an active global player base. Tabletop Simulator (TTS) on Steam allows 3D simulation of virtually any game. Yucata and Bo\u00eete \u00e0 Jeux serve specific niches.\n\nWho it is for: Learners with limited geographic access, unusual schedules, or those wanting to play games not easily accessible physically. Also: anyone wanting to try a game before buying it.\n\nPrimary tradeoff: Lacks the physical and spontaneous social energy of in-person play. Asynchronous play can feel isolating; real-time play requires scheduling across time zones.\n\nMisconception to address: Online boardgaming is not a lesser substitute. BGA alone hosts hundreds of thousands of active players and has a robust club and social system. Many enthusiasts use it as their primary platform for lighter games with geographically dispersed friends.\n\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nCHANNEL 5: CONVENTIONS\n\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\nWhat they are: Events ranging from small local one-day cons to large international festivals (PAX Unplugged, UK Games Expo, Essen Spiel). Feature open gaming halls, publisher demos, and structured tournaments.\n\nWho it is for: Learners who want full immersion in the hobby's community \u2014 best experienced after establishing some connection to the local or online community first.\n\nPrimary tradeoff: High time and financial investment. But the density of enthusiasts and shared context makes starting games with strangers unusually easy. The social barrier to initiating play at a convention is essentially zero \u2014 it is the explicit social norm of the environment."
            },
            {
              "blockId": "cb-04-11",
              "type": "text",
              "content": "THE 30-DAY INTEGRATION PLAN\n\nEntering a new community is the same structure as building any relationship: research, first contact, reciprocity. The 30-day plan puts a timeline on it.\n\nWEEKS 1\u20132: RESEARCH AND CHOOSE\n\u2022 Identify your best-fit channel using the tradeoff analysis above. Consider: geography (do local options exist?), schedule (can you commit to a weekly or monthly event?), and social preference (small established group vs. open platform).\n\u2022 For FLGS: find the nearest store, confirm their game night schedule, note which games they typically play.\n\u2022 For BGG: find your regional guild, read three months of posts to understand the group's culture and who the regulars are before making first contact.\n\u2022 For BGA: create a free account and play three games in casual or open rooms to learn the interface before engaging socially.\n\u2022 Apply Principle 3 from Section 3 to yourself: your first visit is not a commitment to join; it is a low-cost experiment. You are allowed to go once and decide it is not the right fit.\n\nWEEK 3: FIRST CONTACT\n\u2022 For FLGS: arrive on game night. Introduce yourself to the person at the welcome desk or a staff member. Say: 'I am looking for people to play with \u2014 is this a good night to try?' Direct, specific, low-threshold \u2014 exactly the Section 3 ask structure applied to a community rather than a single friend.\n\u2022 For BGG guilds: post a concise introduction. Use your Section 1 game taxonomy knowledge: name three games you enjoy, spanning light to mid-weight, so the group can gauge your experience level. Express what you are looking for.\n\u2022 For BGA: join one open game, introduce yourself briefly in the chat, and play to the end regardless of how it goes.\n\nWEEK 4: INVEST IN RECIPROCITY\n\u2022 Return once more. Consistency signals genuine interest to an established community \u2014 attending once might be curiosity; attending twice is commitment.\n\u2022 Contribute something before being asked: suggest a game at the FLGS night, respond helpfully to someone's BGG post, offer a game recommendation in the BGA chat. Reciprocity is the mechanism of community membership. You do not join a community by attending it; you join it by contributing to it."
            },
